In this sentence:

"Heute hatte ich eine sehr interessante Idee"

Why is "ich" in the 3rd position since it is the subject of the sentence?

### Answer
In the sentence "Heute hatte ich eine sehr interessante Idee," the subject is "ich" (I) and it appears in the third position, following the adverb "heute" (today) and the past tense verb "hatte" (had).

In German, the word order of a sentence is often flexible, but the basic word order for a simple sentence is subject-verb-object (SVO). However, in the sentence you provided, there is no object, and the sentence begins with an adverb that modifies the verb. When an adverb is used at the beginning of a sentence, it is often followed by the verb, which means that the subject (in this case, "ich") must come after the verb. Therefore, the word order of this sentence is "Adverb - Verb - Subject - Predicate" (A-V-S-P).

So, in this sentence, "ich" is in the third position because the adverb "heute" is occupying the first position, and the verb "hatte" is in the second position, followed by the subject "ich" and the predicate "eine sehr interessante Idee" (a very interesting idea).

